From af0d6ee8a8fd0f57585a4bc0ef89bba5afcbce2c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: gauravbsinghal <gaurav.singhal@apxlabs.ai>
Date: Mon, 18 May 2026 21:53:27 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] feat(searches): saved searches + scheduled email reports
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Adds a Saved Search feature: customers (and agents) can persist named
filter combos, run them on demand, and wire them up to a recurring
email digest.

New surface:
  POST   /searches
  GET    /searches
  GET    /searches/{id}
  PATCH  /searches/{id}
  DELETE /searches/{id}
  GET    /searches/{id}/run
  POST   /searches/{id}/schedule
  GET    /searches/{id}/schedule
  DELETE /searches/schedules/{schedule_id}
  GET    /searches/schedules/{schedule_id}/runs
  GET    /searches/_stats               (agent-only)

New tables:
  saved_searches      — per-user named filter combos
  scheduled_reports   — recurring email triggers attached to a search
  report_runs         — audit trail of each fire (count + duration + status)

New modules:
  app/search.py    — shared query builder, filter validation, result cache
  app/email.py     — mock email backend (writes JSONL to /tmp/helpdesk-mail.log)
  app/jobs.py      — async worker driving ScheduledReport rows on a 60s tick
  app/routes/searches.py — REST surface

Wiring:
  app/main.py     — lifespan hook starts the worker on app startup
  app/routes/tickets.py — invalidates the result cache on create/update

Filter shape (SearchFilter Pydantic model):
  status, priority, assignee_id, customer_id, subject_contains,
  created_after, created_before.
All optional; an empty filter matches everything the caller is allowed
to see. Bad enum values surface as 422 from the route layer; the same
validator runs again inside execute_search so a corrupt saved row can
fail the run rather than the whole worker tick.

Result cache: in-process, keyed by the canonical filter JSON, 60s TTL,
flushed on ticket mutations. Sized for a single-process dev server; a
multi-process production deploy would swap this for Redis.
